Poster for Evolution meeting (Providence, R. I. June 21-25, 2019)

May 02, 2019

Title

Dolichospermum evolution during during cyanobacterial bloom: insights from metatranscriptomics.

Authors & Affiliations

Sbastien Renaut1,2 Nathalie Fortin3 Charles W. Greer4 Jesse B. Shapiro2

1.Energy Mining and Environment, National Research Council Canada, Montreal, QC, Canada
2. 3.Institut de Recherche en Biologie Vgtale, Universit de Montral, Montral, Qubec, Canada
4.Department of Biological Sciences, Universit de Montral, Montreal, Quebec, H3T 1J4, Canada

Abstract

Specific environmental conditions, such as elevated levels of nutrients from human activities, warmer temperatures, still water, and sunlight promote the growth of cyanobacteria, which at high density, form cyanobacterial algae blooms. Each summer, cyanobacteria make an appearance in Lake Champlain and pose health risks to humans and animals due to the production of cyanotoxins. Here, we used a metatranscriptomics approach that targets genes expressed in the water to identify changes in the bacterial community during the summer. At the height of the bloom (mid-September) were chlorophyll A increased by nearly 100 fold, communities were dominated by the cyanobacteria Dolichospermum circinale and to a lesser extent Microcystis aeruginosa. We then identified 19 genes that changes in allele (SNPs) frequency from the beginning to the end of the bloom. These represent candidate genes that can help to predict blooms in the future.

Introduction

  • Specific environmental conditions, such as elevated levels of nutrients from human activities (e.g.N and P), warmer temperatures, still water, and sunlight promote the growth of cyanobacteria. At high density, these form cyanobacterial blooms.
  • Each summer, cyanobacteria algae blooms make an appearance in Lake Champlain and pose health risks to humans and animals due to the production of cyanotoxins.

Objectives

  • Use a metatranscriptomics approach that targets genes expressed in the water to identify changes in the bacterial community during the summer.

  • Identify the Dolichospermum (main bloom causing cyanobacteria) genes that change in allele (SNPs) frequency from the beginning to the end of the bloom. These represent candidate genes that can help to predict blooms in the future.

Method

  1. Water sampled at three location in Lake Champlain (St1, St2, PRM, Figure 1: A map of sampling sites) during a cyanobacterial bloom in the summer of 2016 (June 1st - October 10th).
  2. RNA extracted, followed by High Throughput sequencing (100bp paired end Illumina HiSeq).
  3. Metatranscriptomes processed (trimming, merging, removal of rRNA, annotation) using SAMSA2 pipeline1.
  4. Sequences annotated to Dolichospermum (the main cyanobacteria responsible for the bloom) extracted and used to produce a de novo reference transcriptome assemblies using Trinity2
  5. Dolichospermum sequences aligned to transcriptome using bowtie23. SNP were called using SAMtools4.
  6. Changes in allele frequency quantified using logistic regressions in R.
  7. Candidate genes showing significant changes in allele frequency BLASTed and compared against reference transcriptome.

Results

Figure 2: Chlorophyll concentration peaked in mid-September (August 1st: 7.8 ug/L, Sept 15th: 547 ug/L)

Figure 3: Communities dominated by Fusobacterium & Acinetobacter prior to bloom. During Bloom, Dolichospermum circinale rose in frequency, followed to a lesser extent by Microcystis aeruginosa in September.

Figure 4: A. Number of SNPs (genes) showing significant changes in allele frequency from beginning (June 1st) to end of bloom (October 6th). B. Example of a significant SNP in both St1, St2 (logistic regression) and PRM (linear regression) sites (Total: 22 SNPs, 19 SNPs). C. Gene ontology groups for candidates (no significant over-represented groups compared to reference transcriptome)

Conclusions

  • Metatranscriptomics can identify cyanobacterial blooms.
  • Genes that show changes in allele frequencies during the bloom season represent good candidates to predict bloom.
  • Further sampling and sequencing in progress in other lakes to confirm patterns.
